Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bolbec","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: habitational name for someone from Houlbec, the name of several places in Normandy. It is formed with fused preposition <i>d(e)</i> ‘from’. Compare   Dalbec  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dalbec","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Euclide, Jean-Marc, Rosaire.","Altered form of French   Dolbec  ."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":79,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":88,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda Bolbec was born about 1136, in Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Elias de Giffard and Ala d'Evreaux. She had at least 2 daughters with Godfrey de Scudamore. She died in Gloucestershire, England."},"et":{"Abt 1136–":"umbes 1136–Surnud","1100–1159":"1100–1159","1110–1135":"1110–1135","1136–Female":"1136–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1128–1190":"1128–1190","1135–1203":"1135–1203","1155–1204":"1155–1204","1060–1130":"1060–1130","–1121":"–1121","1190":"1190","1099":"1099","1121":"1121","1110":"1110","1130":"1130","Abt 1136":"umbes 1136","1060":"1060","1128":"1128","1215":"1215","1204":"1204","1203":"1203","1159":"1159","1224":"1224","1136":"1136","1135":"1135","Abt 1155":"umbes 1155","1155":"1155","1100":"1100","Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England":"Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gloucester